High Performance Computing 2024 - Part 1

The requirements for this exercise are described here.
In summary, the assignment consists of the evaluation and comparison of different algorithms to perform collective communication operations among the nodes of a HPC infrastructure. The experiments are carried out on ORFEO using the OSU benchmarks for MPI operations.

The project was developed using the following software stack:
- OpenMPI/4.1.6 with the GNU compiler,
- Python 3.10.12 for scripting and data analysis.


Here is a summary of the contents of this report.
• Section 1 specifies which operations and algorithms have been considered and describes their functioning from a theoretical point of view.
• Section 2 is about the benchmark functions and their parameters.
• Section 3 evaluates the choice of the mapping strategy.
• Section 4 presents the results and compares the different algorithms’ performances.

Section 1

The OSU benchmarks include a wide range of communication operations in different programming languages.
This assignment focuses on blocking collective MPI benchmarks in C, specifically covering MPI_Bcast and MPI_Reduce.

In the broadcast operation, a process called root sends a message with the same data to all processes in the communicator.
Different communication topologies can be selected, each implemented by a specific algorithm. The list of algorithms implemented in the OSU benchmarks can be retrieved with: $ompi_info --param coll tuned --level 5 | grep "Which bcast algorithm is used".

If the user does not explicitly select an algorithm (or selects 0: "ignore"), the choice of the algorithm defaults to the MPI library’s internal optimization.
This experiment will use the default algorithm as a baseline to evaluate the performance of other algorithms:
• chain: processes are arranged in a chain, with each process receiving the whole data at once from the previous process and forwarding it to the next; the root process sends the data to all other processes one by one, amounting to a flat-tree communication graph;
• pipeline: employs the same topology as the chain algorithm, but the data is split into segments that are passed along, allowing each intermediate process to forward the previous segment while receiving a new one;
• binary tree: the root sends data to two children, each of which sends data to two more and so on, doubling the number of processes reached at each step.

The reduce operation combines data from all processes into a single result at a designated root process.  The algorithms for reduction use the same topologies but with distinct mechanisms:
• linear: non-root processes send their data directly to the root, which applies the reduction operation as each message is received (flat-tree communication graph);
• pipeline: Data is split into chunks, with each chunk reduced by the sender before being forwarded to the next process, allowing overlap between communication and computation;
• binary: Each process collects data from its children, performs the reduction, and sends the result to its parent, utilizing a tree structure.

A simple investigation, involving the parameters i (number of iterations for timing) and w (set number of warmup iterations to skip before timing), has been carried out to verify whether setting values different from the default ones would affect the results.
For a set of experiments, the performance of the communication was measured and compared, both varying the total number of iterations and the number of warmup iterations:

The data and plots for all the tests are available here.
The results show that, at least for the selected settings, increasing the number of iterations for timing and the number of warmup iterations does not yield consistent variations in the results. Thus, from this point on, any further experiment will use the parameters with their default values. 

Section 3

The way the processes are mapped to the computational resources is a crucial factor for the performance of the algorithms.
As pointed out in the OpenMPI documentation, mpirun automatically binds processes to core if the number of processes is <=2 and to package otherwise, or to none when the binding pattern is oversubscribed.

In this section, some experiments are presented where the mapping strategy is explicitly defined for each execution. The goal is to determine if the mapping affects the communication latencies in a significant way.


For this specific architecture, mapping by L3cache, by socket and by NUMA coincide, since each node has exactly 2 sockets, 2 NUMA regions and 2 L3caches.


As mentioned in this paper, at each step the time of communication is dominated by the longest communication.
For intra-node communications, it is reasonable to imagine that communications between CPUs in different NUMA regions take longer than those in the same region.


Actually, when messages are smaller, the latency introduced by NUMA can be more pronounced because the data transfer itself is relatively quick. However, for larger messages, the cost of moving the data dominates the initial latency overhead introduced by NUMA locality, and there might be additional communication overhead (e.g., message segmentation, buffer management), making the NUMA effects are less visible.
Anyway, inter-node communication is likely to have the longest latency, since the transmission of a message between nodes requires the use of a network channel.

Based on these considerations, and considering that different algorithms for a collective operation create different topologies, it is reasonable to assume that the mapping strategy might affect the total communication time for a certain algorithm by impacting the needed point-to-point communications among CPUs and their ordering.


When employing the pipeline algorithm, mapping by node increases the number of transmissions through the network channels, and for small messages this penalizes the overall performance. However, for bigger messages, the other mappings become less efficient because of resource contention.
For binary tree algorithm, the node mapping outperforms the others for any message size. The number of inter-node communications is the same for all the mapping strategies, but when mapping by node communication between nodes happens earlier in the broadcast process. The different results might be due to internal communication delays in each node due to resource contention among the processes, for the mappings where the inter-node communications occur just on the bottom of the tree.

Similar observations hold also in the case of the reduce operation. All the data and the plots can be found here.

Section 4

Here, the results of the experiments are reported.


The baseline, which chooses automatically the implementation of the collective operation, outperforms all of the considered algorithm, except for the binary tree, which shows up to be especially efficient for larger numbers of processes.
The pipeline algorithm surprisingly performs much worse than the chain algorithm, of which it represents a parallelization, for any problem size.
All of this can be better visualized by comparing the performance of the algorithm on the same problem size. 


Unfortunately, the data for the reduce operation is incomplete.
However, these partial results show very similar performance for the baseline and the basic linear algorithm, with the binary tree algorithm performing much better especially for big problem sizes.
